00:01:49.250 --> 00:01:51.080
Let's get started.

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:53.980
So first off, what is
ubiquitous computing?

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:56.520
It's simply a fancy
phrase for technology

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:00.370
that's accessible to the user
whenever and wherever they

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:02.780
want or need it.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:04.260
That's it.

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:07.320
It could be outside when
they're going for a bike ride

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.949
or having some friends
over to watch cat videos.

00:02:09.949 --> 00:02:13.830
Or maybe it's time
for a road trip.

00:02:13.830 --> 00:02:16.050
Your users can be in
any of those situations.

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:18.700
And you don't want them to have
to think about what device they

00:02:18.700 --> 00:02:20.870
need to get to your service.

00:02:20.870 --> 00:02:24.410
Instead, you're going to want an
experience that presents itself

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:27.120
to the user wherever
it makes sense

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:29.702
by building an app that
runs on whatever device

00:02:29.702 --> 00:02:30.410
they have nearby.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.520
And many people look at
the evolution of computing

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:36.050
like this.

00:02:38.750 --> 00:02:41.570
It's always about the next
device-- big computer,

00:02:41.570 --> 00:02:44.190
little computer,
littler computer.

00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:47.180
What's the next thing in
this linear progression?

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:49.310
But really, our
present and future

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:51.791
looks quite a bit different.

00:02:51.791 --> 00:02:55.500
It looks a lot more
like this, right?

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:58.301
We use a bunch of technology
in different ways.

00:02:58.301 --> 00:02:59.800
And we often do
that simultaneously.

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:05.270
In fact, the growth of
these connected devices

00:03:05.270 --> 00:03:06.870
is staggering.

00:03:06.870 --> 00:03:09.215
Although the number
in 2020 depends

00:03:09.215 --> 00:03:12.230
on who you ask-- it can be
a little bit different--

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:14.195
It's always more
than you can imagine.

00:03:14.195 --> 00:03:15.820
Now, I didn't throw
out the units here.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:18.070
Does anybody want to tell
me what the units are there?

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:21.400
Millions?

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:22.850
It's billions.

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:26.665
200 billion devices in 2020.

00:03:26.665 --> 00:03:29.290
And you can actually break this
number down because 200 billion

00:03:29.290 --> 00:03:30.900
is sort of like this
abstract number.

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:32.330
Think of it this way.

00:03:32.330 --> 00:03:40.340
26 smart devices for every
human on the planet in 2020.

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:42.250
A lot.

00:03:42.250 --> 00:03:45.310
But not everybody has 26 in
their pockets at the same time,

00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:45.810
right?

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:47.420
This is across industries.

00:03:47.420 --> 00:03:51.270
But think about the number of
devices that are going to be

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:53.145
and already are in our world.

00:03:55.691 --> 00:03:56.940
Here's another number for you.

00:03:59.742 --> 00:04:03.010
Hey, this is really interesting,
especially for us, right?

00:04:03.010 --> 00:04:06.630
Gartner has estimated
half of IOT solutions

00:04:06.630 --> 00:04:10.030
will be from startups
less than three years old.

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:11.460
Half.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:14.340
So the question really is,
have you already started

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.430
building for this reality?

00:04:17.430 --> 00:04:21.470
The good news is it's not that
hard to deal with, not as hard

00:04:21.470 --> 00:04:23.280
as it might seem.

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:26.260
The explosion in form factors
is manageable by having

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:30.790
a strong core platform that
lends itself to extensibility.

00:04:30.790 --> 00:04:34.280
So you can think less about a
new project for each new device

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:36.205
and more about a
versatile solution

00:04:36.205 --> 00:04:39.120
that you can extend
for new form factors

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:41.940
as they become available.

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:45.040
And these platforms that
help you, they exist today.

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.760
I'm going to show you a
working example in a bit.

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:49.550
But before we dig
into some code,

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:52.710
this is what it
looks like logically.

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:55.640
Now, the traditional approach
to supporting different devices

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.590
is to make an app for
each device and platform

00:04:59.590 --> 00:05:01.995
as they become available
and adopted by users.

00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:07.560
Like my animation?

00:05:07.560 --> 00:05:09.960
This has typically
meant a new project

00:05:09.960 --> 00:05:13.210
for each and every device
developed and supported

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:14.610
independently.

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:15.510
Just crazy.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:19.110
And the ironic thing is that
we as developers are already

00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:22.510
thinking about this
experience as part

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:25.900
of a single whole experience
for the user across devices.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:28.900
It's just silly to approach
these as separate projects.

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:31.440
Instead, you want to take
the longer lens view.

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:34.670
Think about having a view
into your service from each

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:36.090
and every device
that makes sense.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:39.000
Your model and controller
are on a central device

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.020
or in the cloud.

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:42.495
But then the wearable,
in the living room,

00:05:42.495 --> 00:05:45.950
in the car's a different
view into that service.

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:48.160
And this is the definition
of ubiquitous computing

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:49.040
again, right?

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:50.920
It's where your
service is available

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:54.246
anywhere and everywhere.

00:05:54.246 --> 00:05:55.620
Now, each of you
and your service

00:05:55.620 --> 00:05:57.090
is going to differ
slightly, right?

00:05:57.090 --> 00:05:59.340
It's going to look a little
bit different on the wrist

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:00.730
than it will in the car.

00:06:00.730 --> 00:06:02.750
And that's what you want
to spend your time on.

00:06:02.750 --> 00:06:04.830
You don't want to have to
spend your time on figuring out

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:06.590
the glue in between
all these things.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:13.100
So what we'll do is we'll
jump right into best practices

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:16.520
here so that we can think
about how to conceptualize

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:17.830
that experience.

00:06:17.830 --> 00:06:20.020
And people no longer
need to sit at a desk

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:22.040
to get the benefits
of technology.

00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:24.820
Experiences that we build
can do more than just

00:06:24.820 --> 00:06:27.510
allow for that usage, right?

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:31.160
As I've been saying, they
can assume that usage

00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:33.160
throughout the day
and in the world.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:35.530
They can do more
than just work nicely

00:06:35.530 --> 00:06:37.400
with existing
technology in our lives.

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:39.550
They can work seamlessly
across all of it.

00:06:39.550 --> 00:06:42.490
Now, with that in mind,
these best practices

00:06:42.490 --> 00:06:44.880
will help us navigate the
issues, big and small,

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:47.660
that we develop in this way.

00:06:47.660 --> 00:06:50.525
And a note about
these best practices

00:06:50.525 --> 00:06:52.420
is that they're
guidelines that apply

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:55.110
to your experience
on each device

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:58.400
as well as the greater
experience across all devices,

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:01.700
which is a great litmus test
for best practices in this area.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:04.399
And make them great for
ubiquitous computing

00:07:04.399 --> 00:07:06.190
when you're thinking
about both the smaller

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:08.750
picture and the bigger
picture across everything

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:10.560
at the same time.

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:14.470
The first one is sort
of obvious, simple.

00:07:14.470 --> 00:07:15.940
Now, think about it this way.

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:18.800
The user experience
should be so simple

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:23.500
that it feels effortless,
almost magical.

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:26.070
In the long run,
users always prefer

00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:31.070
simplicity and reliability
over quantity of features.

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:33.250
Whatever user problem
you solve, make

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:36.010
sure to address
that really well.

00:07:36.010 --> 00:07:38.690
And never get in the
way of that solution.

00:07:38.690 --> 00:07:41.180
A great example of this
is a messaging app.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:43.510
I love messaging
on Android Wear.

00:07:43.510 --> 00:07:44.330
I get a message.

00:07:44.330 --> 00:07:45.920
And I can reply by voice.

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:47.810
It's so intuitive and simple.

00:07:47.810 --> 00:07:51.020
It just makes sense.

00:07:51.020 --> 00:07:54.130
The next one is contextual.

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:58.830
Now, being contextual is
really about being relevant.

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:03.220
Take into account the time, the
location, and even the activity

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:05.510
the user's involved
in to provide them

00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:09.540
with the most useful experience
wherever they happen to be.

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:12.640
As an example, I love the
idea of a shopping list

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:16.470
that automatically comes
up as I get into the store

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:20.030
and, before I leave, maybe sends
me a notification of any items

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:21.690
I might have missed.

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:24.980
In this case, we're providing
information to the user

00:08:24.980 --> 00:08:28.090
before they have to
ask because we're

00:08:28.090 --> 00:08:30.890
taking into account their
context for them, which

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:33.690
leads me to this idea.

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:38.900
The experience should be so fast
that it should feel immediate.

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:42.610
Now, being contextual
can help with this.

00:08:42.610 --> 00:08:45.630
But it's also about
micro-interactions.

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:48.140
Remember that you're not
trying to distract and occupy

00:08:48.140 --> 00:08:49.190
the user.

00:08:49.190 --> 00:08:51.260
You want to present just
the right information

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:53.530
right away so they
can get what they need

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:56.750
and keep living their lives.

00:08:56.750 --> 00:08:59.780
A great example of this is
Voice Search on Android TV.

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:01.720
The user can say what
show they want to watch.

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:03.880
And any app that's
set up for search

00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:06.730
can launch that
content for them.

00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:09.370
Another great example
is Auto Play and queuing

00:09:09.370 --> 00:09:10.670
on Google Cast.

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:13.020
The next episode can
just come right on

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:15.630
so the user doesn't
have to stop and find it

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:17.400
when they're binge watching.

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:19.930
I do on the weekends.

00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:23.060
The last thing is extensible.

00:09:23.060 --> 00:09:24.820
And you're going to
want to build your app

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:28.630
and experience to be as
extensible as possible.

00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:31.010
Where are the places
that your user will want

00:09:31.010 --> 00:09:33.760
to user service in the future?

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:35.980
And how can you build
that into your core app

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:40.040
now so that the overall
experience that the user has

00:09:40.040 --> 00:09:45.600
is in hand whenever and wherever
it makes sense for them?

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:46.410
So those are them.

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:48.750
Oh, an example of this-- music.

00:09:48.750 --> 00:09:52.120
I love listening to
music wherever I want.

00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:54.630
And it turns out, I think,
everybody's that way.

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:57.460
That might be at home
in the living room.

00:09:57.460 --> 00:10:02.860
That might be on the go while
I'm on a run or in the car.

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:04.920
So there you are-- a
handful of principles

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:07.880
to help you refine the design
of your user experience

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:12.330
and reach your users in
an undeniably useful way.

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:14.220
That's really key.

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:15.890
We found when working
with developers

00:10:15.890 --> 00:10:18.990
that these guidelines help the
most when working with new form

00:10:18.990 --> 00:10:21.060
factors, understanding
right away how

00:10:21.060 --> 00:10:24.650
to contextualize and measure
your work for success.

00:10:24.650 --> 00:10:27.330
And that's why we created
a design sprint technique

00:10:27.330 --> 00:10:29.940
for learning the design
principles for new form factors

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:31.220
in particular.

00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:33.620
The material for one
of these design sprints

00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:35.410
was just launched
yesterday morning

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:37.190
on developers.google.com.

00:10:37.190 --> 00:10:39.320
And many of you who
arrived a session early

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:42.150
may have found a play
book on your seat.

00:10:42.150 --> 00:10:45.670
Design sprints are a great
way to learn immediately

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:49.930
and to try out design principles
for these new form factors.

00:10:49.930 --> 00:10:52.087
And then you can apply
them to your own project

00:10:52.087 --> 00:10:53.420
with the comfort of familiarity.

00:10:56.870 --> 00:10:57.550
All right.

00:10:57.550 --> 00:11:00.440
Let's look at a practical
solution, shall we?

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:02.990
One that you can
download, compile, adjust,

00:11:02.990 --> 00:11:04.050
and learn from.

00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:07.370
A sample code usually just
shows you a narrow view

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:09.630
at a partial solution,
which is great

00:11:09.630 --> 00:11:12.210
if you want to know just
how one thing works.

00:11:12.210 --> 00:11:15.550
However, when you want to see
how everything fits together,

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:17.882
you need a fully
functioning example.

00:11:17.882 --> 00:11:19.840
And this is particularly
important for building

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:23.050
across devices because how
everything fits together

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:25.430
is the thing.

00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:28.820
And we recently released a
simple but complete app just

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:30.280
for this purpose.

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:31.855
This is not the
only kind of thing

00:11:31.855 --> 00:11:33.650
that you can build
to be ubiquitous.

00:11:33.650 --> 00:11:34.430
Remember that.

00:11:34.430 --> 00:11:37.560
But rather, it's just a
look at one kind of app

00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:41.490
and how it can be built
with these ideas in mind.

00:11:41.490 --> 00:11:43.254
The universal
Android Music Player.

00:11:43.254 --> 00:11:45.420
Remember I was just talking
about listening to music

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:46.280
everywhere?

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:48.250
This app helps you do that.

00:11:48.250 --> 00:11:56.160
And it works on your phone,
your watch, your television--

00:11:56.160 --> 00:12:03.950
both Android TV soon and Google
Cast-- and of course, your car.

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:06.750
And it's completely
open source on GitHub.

00:12:06.750 --> 00:12:07.490
There's the URL.

00:12:11.231 --> 00:12:12.980
Now, let's say you
have a media app that's

00:12:12.980 --> 00:12:14.410
built around an activity.

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:15.430
This is pretty common.

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:20.200
And that was just fine
for an app on a device.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:23.660
But if you want to support more
devices, what you usually do

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:25.800
is you either expand
that activity,

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:30.290
or you create new ones
for each new device.

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:33.620
That's still not so bad until
you realize that you probably

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:36.880
have to revisit your
app's overall design each

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:40.070
and every time to coordinate
new message passing, play

00:12:40.070 --> 00:12:41.930
locks, and that kind of thing.

00:12:41.930 --> 00:12:46.220
Instead, you're going to want a
solid core central service that

00:12:46.220 --> 00:12:49.670
extends easily to
each new form factor.

00:12:49.670 --> 00:12:54.260
There's an Android API that
makes this straightforward.

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:57.640
UAMP is built around this
media browser service and media

00:12:57.640 --> 00:12:59.400
session.

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:02.470
So this is a way that you would
build your app on Lollipop

00:13:02.470 --> 00:13:05.060
so that you could have media
keep playing in the background,

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:08.060
be controlled from the
lock screen, and so forth.

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:10.520
It's also a great way to
allow multiple devices

00:13:10.520 --> 00:13:13.880
to act as consumers
of a central service

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:16.124
rather than everything built
in activities that need

00:13:16.124 --> 00:13:17.290
to independently coordinate.

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:23.430
The media browser service
maintains a tree structure

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.860
of all your media, such
as a collection of music.

00:13:26.860 --> 00:13:31.290
And this could be either
streamed or stored locally.

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:33.950
Media Session tracks
the current state

00:13:33.950 --> 00:13:37.200
of what your app is playing.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:39.160
Now, here's where
it gets interesting.

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:41.350
Everything, whether
it's your phone app,

00:13:41.350 --> 00:13:43.730
Android TV, Android
Auto-- they're

00:13:43.730 --> 00:13:46.960
all consumers of the Media
Browser Service and Media

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:48.840
Session.

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:50.620
Let's say you've got
your phone hooked up

00:13:50.620 --> 00:13:54.160
to Android Auto like this.

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:56.710
So the companion app
on the left, that's

00:13:56.710 --> 00:13:58.640
the Android Auto Companion app.

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:02.170
And that app is responsible
for drawing the user interface

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:05.660
and sending those pixels
to the vehicle display.

00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:10.010
This app also connects to
the Media Browser Service.

00:14:10.010 --> 00:14:11.970
And it queries it to
get the tree structure

00:14:11.970 --> 00:14:14.280
of your apps media library.

00:14:14.280 --> 00:14:16.940
The driver of the car
then selects the song,

00:14:16.940 --> 00:14:19.630
either the touch screen
or through voice search,

00:14:19.630 --> 00:14:22.390
and then Android Auto
will use Media Session

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:24.560
to run your callbacks.

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:27.810
And this is great on Android
Auto because as a developer,

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:30.010
you never have to worry
about the details of making

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:31.980
a user interface that's
safe for driving.

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:34.270
Android Auto takes care
of all of that for you.

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:37.710
It just needs the music service
available to get the data

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:40.460
and handle playback.

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:42.900
And the app on the left,
it could be anything.

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:44.360
It could be Android Wear .

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:47.530
It could be just another
activity in your same app

00:14:47.530 --> 00:14:49.110
handling Android TV.

00:14:49.110 --> 00:14:51.380
Or maybe it's
handling Google Cast.

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:54.660
Any of these will work
because of how it's set up.

00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:57.880
We don't have to rewire the
app each and every time we

00:14:57.880 --> 00:14:59.370
add a new form factor.

00:14:59.370 --> 00:15:02.060
Instead, we have this
solid central service

00:15:02.060 --> 00:15:05.480
that extends easily to
each new form factor.

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:07.400
You simply access
the music service

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:12.424
for any context that
makes sense for your user.

00:15:12.424 --> 00:15:13.840
Now, remember what
I said earlier.

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:16.080
This is certainly
not the only way

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:18.460
to make a ubiquitous app or
the only ubiquitous app that

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:19.380
makes sense.

00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:20.810
It simply gives
you an idea of how

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:23.140
to structure a common
app such as a music

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:25.210
player for extensibility.

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:27.410
The specific APIs
you use are of course

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:29.440
going to depend
on your use case,

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:32.330
how you implement the best
practices we talked about,

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:34.909
and where you keep your
model and your controller.

00:15:34.909 --> 00:15:35.950
It could be on the phone.

00:15:35.950 --> 00:15:37.070
It could be in the cloud.

00:15:37.070 --> 00:15:39.320
It could be wherever that
make sense for your service.

00:15:41.670 --> 00:15:44.420
Let's take a look at
